{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585168"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:04:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:04:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14925"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14925"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.09,0.88,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7613"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115404"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7613"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14925"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97407"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4908"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"8093"},{"type":"tags","id":"8542"},{"type":"tags","id":"9979"},{"type":"tags","id":"9980"},{"type":"tags","id":"9981"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18618"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18619"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115404"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Major Histocompatibility Complex (MHC) molecules play a crucial role in presenting antigens to T cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the distribution of MHC molecules in human cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Class I MHC molecules are found only on immune cells","Class II MHC molecules are found on all nucleated cells","Class I MHC molecules on all nucleated cells, Class II MHC molecules on antigen-presenting cells only","Both Class I and Class II MHC molecules are found on all nucleated cells","Both Class I and Class II MHC molecules are found only on professional antigen presenting cells"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass I on all nucleated cells, Class II on antigen presenting cells only\u003C/strong\u003E. This distribution pattern is crucial for proper immune function. Class I MHC presents intracellular antigens to CD8+ T cells, enabling surveillance for viral infections or cellular transformation in all tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass I MHC molecules are found only on immune cells\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as Class I MHC is actually found on all nucleated cells. \u003Cstrong\u003EClass II MHC molecules are found on all nucleated cells\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because Class II MHC is restricted to professional antigen presenting cells. \u003Cstrong\u003EBoth Class I and Class II MHC molecules are found on all nucleated cells\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect since only Class I MHC is widely distributed. \u003Cstrong\u003EBoth Class I and Class II MHC molecules are found only on professional antigen presenting cells\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because while these cells express both classes, Class I MHC is more widely distributed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProfessional antigen presenting cells (dendritic cells, macrophages, and B cells) uniquely express Class II MHC to present extracellular antigens to CD4+ T cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Class I Major Histocompatibility Complex (MHC) molecules are expressed on all nucleated cells to present intracellular antigens to CD8+ T cells","Class II MHC molecules are only expressed on professional antigen presenting cells (dendritic cells, macrophages, B cells) to present extracellular antigens to CD4+ T cells","This differential distribution pattern ensures appropriate immune responses to different types of threats"],"references":["Janeway CA Jr, Travers P, Walport M, et al. Immunobiology: The Immune System in Health and Disease. 5th edition. New York: Garland Science; 2001. Generation of lymphocytes in bone marrow and thymus. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK27123/","Playfair, J. H. L., \u0026 Chain, B. M. (2012). Immunology at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Marshall JS, Warrington R, Watson W, Kim HL. An introduction to immunology and immunopathology. Allergy Asthma Clin Immunol. 2018 Sep 12;14(Suppl 2):49. doi: 10.1186/s13223-018-0278-1. PMID: 30263032; PMCID: PMC6156898"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97407"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14925"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97407"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T15:41:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T15:42:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7613"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115404"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":